Document: OpenXR Settings
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/openxr_settings.rst
Summary: This document outlines the settings available for configuring OpenXR in Godot Engine.

OpenXR Settings

This page details the settings available in the OpenXR project settings.

OpenXR is an open standard that aims to simplify virtual reality development by providing a common interface for VR hardware and software. Godot supports OpenXR, allowing developers to target various VR platforms with a single codebase.

To access the OpenXR settings, navigate to Project -> Project Settings -> XR.

General Settings
----------------

.. csv-table::
   :header: Name,Type,Description,Default

   OpenXR/Render Backend,String,Specifies the rendering backend to use for OpenXR. Options include Vulkan and OpenGL. If not specified, Godot will attempt to auto-detect.,
   OpenXR/Enable Render Doc,Boolean,Enables RenderDoc integration for debugging. This is useful for diagnosing rendering issues.,False
   OpenXR/Enable Validation Layers,Boolean,Enables validation layers for Vulkan. This can help catch errors during development but may impact performance.,False
   OpenXR/Swapchain Format,String,Specifies the preferred swapchain format for rendering. Common formats include R8G8B8A8_UNORM and R16G16B16A16_SFLOAT.,R8G8B8A8_UNORM
   OpenXR/Enable Hand Tracking,Boolean,Enables hand tracking support if the OpenXR runtime provides it.,False
   OpenXR/Enable Eye Gaze Tracking,Boolean,Enables eye gaze tracking support if the OpenXR runtime provides it.,False

Render Backend
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

The `OpenXR/Render Backend` setting allows you to choose the graphics API used for rendering. The available options depend on your system's capabilities and the OpenXR runtime. Vulkan is generally recommended for its performance benefits.

RenderDoc Integration
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

Enabling `OpenXR/Enable Render Doc` will integrate RenderDoc, a powerful graphics debugger. This is invaluable for identifying and resolving rendering artifacts or performance bottlenecks.

Validation Layers
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

The `OpenXR/Enable Validation Layers` option activates Vulkan validation layers. These layers provide detailed error messages and warnings during development, helping to catch potential issues early. Note that enabling validation layers can introduce a performance overhead, so they should typically be disabled in release builds.

Swapchain Format
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

The `OpenXR/Swapchain Format` setting determines the pixel format used for the swapchain, which is the buffer that holds the rendered image before it's presented to the headset. Choosing an appropriate format can impact visual quality and performance. `R8G8B8A8_UNORM` is a common and widely supported format.

Hand and Eye Gaze Tracking
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

If your VR hardware and OpenXR runtime support hand tracking and eye gaze tracking, you can enable these features using the `OpenXR/Enable Hand Tracking` and `OpenXR/Enable Eye Gaze Tracking` options respectively. These can be used to implement more immersive interactions within your VR applications.

Key Rule: Ensure your OpenXR runtime and hardware support the features you enable in these settings. Incorrect configurations may lead to runtime errors or a lack of functionality.
