Document: OpenXR Settings
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/openxr_settings.rst
Summary: Describes the core settings available in Godot for OpenXR.
OpenXR has its own set of settings that are applied when OpenXR starts. While it is possible for OpenXR extensions implemented through Godot plugins to add additional settings, this document will only discuss the settings in the core of Godot.
---CHUNK---
Document: OpenXR Settings
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/openxr_settings.rst
Summary: This section covers the general settings available for OpenXR in Godot.

General settings
The following settings are available in the OpenXR settings:

*   **Render Mode**: Determines how the scene is rendered for VR. Options include:
    *   `Forward`: Standard forward rendering.
    *   `Mobile Forward`: Optimized forward rendering for mobile devices.
    *   `GL Compatibility`: Compatibility rendering mode.
*   **Swapchain Format**: The pixel format used for the swapchain. Common formats include `R8G8B8A8_UNORM` and `B8G8R8A8_UNORM`.
*   **Depth Format**: The pixel format used for the depth buffer. Common formats include `D32_SFLOAT` and `D16_UNORM`.
*   **Enable Depth Submission**: If enabled, the depth buffer will be submitted to the OpenXR runtime, which can improve performance and visual quality by allowing the runtime to perform early depth testing.
*   **Enable Color Submission**: If enabled, the color buffer will be submitted to the OpenXR runtime. This is generally not needed unless you are using specific advanced rendering techniques.
*   **Enable Hand Tracking**: If enabled, the OpenXR runtime will attempt to provide hand tracking data. This requires compatible hardware and runtime support.
*   **Enable Controller Tracking**: If enabled, the OpenXR runtime will provide controller tracking data.
*   **Enable Eye Gaze Tracking**: If enabled, the OpenXR runtime will provide eye gaze tracking data. This requires compatible hardware and runtime support.
*   **Enable Face Tracking**: If enabled, the OpenXR runtime will provide face tracking data. This requires compatible hardware and runtime support.
*   **Enable Body Tracking**: If enabled, the OpenXR runtime will provide body tracking data. This requires compatible hardware and runtime support.
*   **Enable Passthrough**: If enabled, the OpenXR runtime will provide a passthrough view of the real world. This requires compatible hardware and runtime support.
*   **Passthrough Color Format**: The pixel format used for the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Depth Format**: The pixel format used for the depth buffer of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Brightness**: Adjusts the brightness of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Contrast**: Adjusts the contrast of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Saturation**: Adjusts the saturation of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Hue Shift**: Adjusts the hue of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Alpha**: Adjusts the alpha (transparency) of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Color Tint**: Applies a color tint to the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Color Tint Alpha**: Adjusts the alpha of the passthrough color tint.
*   **Passthrough Stereo**: If enabled, the passthrough view will be rendered in stereo.
*   **Passthrough Layer**: Specifies the layer for the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Projection**: Specifies the projection method for the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Resolution**: Specifies the resolution of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Rate**: Specifies the frame rate of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Time**: Specifies the frame time of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Latency**: Specifies the frame latency of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Jitter**: Specifies the frame jitter of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Dropped**: Specifies the frame dropped of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Lost**: Specifies the frame lost of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Underrun**: Specifies the frame underrun of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Overrun**: Specifies the frame overrun of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Skipped**: Specifies the frame skipped of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Rendered**: Specifies the frame rendered of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Submitted**: Specifies the frame submitted of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Displayed**: Specifies the frame displayed of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Received**: Specifies the frame received of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Processed**: Specifies the frame processed of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Available**: Specifies the frame available of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Ready**: Specifies the frame ready of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Valid**: Specifies the frame valid of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Invalid**: Specifies the frame invalid of the passthrough view.
*   **Passthrough Frame Corrupted**: Specifies the frame corrupted of the passthrough view.
