Document: OpenXR Settings
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/openxr_settings.rst
Summary: Explains the 'Enabled' setting for the OpenXR module in Godot.
Enabled
This setting enables the OpenXR module when Godot starts. This is required when the Vulkan backend is used. For other backends, you can enable OpenXR at any time by calling initialize on the OpenXRInterface. This also needs to be enabled to get access to the action map editor. You can use the --xr-mode on command line switch to force this to on.
---CHUNK---
Document: OpenXR Settings
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/openxr_settings.rst
Summary: This section describes the default action map setting for OpenXR.

Default Action Map
This specifies the path of the action map file that OpenXR will load and communicate to the XR Runtime.
---CHUNK---
Document: OpenXR Settings
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/openxr_settings.rst
Summary: Explains the 'Form Factor' setting in OpenXR and its implications.

Form Factor
This specifies whether your game is designed for:

*   Head Mounted devices such as a Meta Quest, Valve Index, or Magic Leap,
*   Handheld devices such as phones.

If the device on which you run your game does not match the selection here, OpenXR will fail to initialise.
---CHUNK---
Document: OpenXR Settings
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/openxr_settings.rst
Summary: This section describes the view configuration options available in OpenXR settings for Godot projects.
View Configuration
This specifies the view configuration your game is designed for:
- Mono, your game provides a single image output. E.g. phone based AR;
- Stereo, your game provides stereo image output. E.g. head mounted devices.
If the device on which you run your game does not match the selection here, OpenXR will fail to initialise.
Note: OpenXR has additional view configurations for very specific devices that Godot doesn't support yet. For instance, Varjo headsets have a quad view configuration that outputs two sets of stereo images. These may be supported in the near future.
---CHUNK---
Document: OpenXR Settings
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/openxr_settings.rst
Summary: Explains the concept of reference spaces in OpenXR for mapping virtual and real-world tracking volumes.

Reference Space

Within XR, all elements like the player's head and hands are tracked within a tracking volume. At the base of this tracking volume is our origin point, which maps our virtual space to the real space. There are however different scenarios that place this point in different locations, depending on the XR system used. In OpenXR these scenarios are well defined and selected by setting a reference space.
---CHUNK---
Document: OpenXR Settings
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/openxr_settings.rst
Summary: This section describes the local reference space in OpenXR, its behavior, use cases, and important considerations.
The local reference space places the origin point at the player's head by default. Some XR runtimes reset this origin each time the game starts, while others maintain the position across sessions. This reference space does not prevent the user from physically moving away from the origin. If you need to keep the user within a specific area, such as a vehicle they are controlling, you must implement logic to detect and handle such movements to prevent game-breaking scenarios.

The local reference space is ideal for games like flight simulators or racing simulators. In these cases, the XROrigin3D node should be positioned where the player's head is intended to be. When the user activates the recenter option on their headset (the method varies by XR runtime), the XR runtime repositions the XRCamera3D relative to the XROrigin3D node. Concurrently, the OpenXRInterface emits the pose_recentered signal, allowing your game to respond to this event.

Note: Any other XR tracked elements, such as controllers or anchors, will also be adjusted automatically to maintain their relative positions.

Warning: You should not call center_on_hmd when using this reference space.
---CHUNK---
Document: OpenXR Settings
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/openxr_settings.rst
Summary: Explains the Stage reference space in OpenXR, its behavior with user recentering, and how to recenter the XR origin in Godot.
The stage reference space is the default and places the origin point at the center of the play space. For XR runtimes that support guardian boundaries, this location and orientation are often user-defined. Other runtimes may determine this point differently, but it remains a stationary point in the real world. This reference space is ideal for room-scale games where players move within a large area or for games requiring mode switching.

When a user enacts the recenter option on their headset (the method varies by XR runtime), the XR runtime does not change the origin point. Instead, the OpenXRInterface emits the `pose_recentered` signal, and the game must react appropriately to avoid store rejections.

In Godot, recentering can be achieved by calling the `center_on_hmd` function on the XRServer.
- Calling `XRServer.center_on_hmd(XRServer.RESET_BUT_KEEP_TILT, false)` moves the XRCamera3D node to the XROrigin3D node, similar to the Local reference space.
- Calling `XRServer.center_on_hmd(XRServer.RESET_BUT_KEEP_TILT, true)` moves the XRCamera3D node above the XROrigin3D node while maintaining the player's height, similar to the Local Floor reference space.
Note: Any other XR tracked elements, such as controllers or anchors, will also be adjusted accordingly.
---CHUNK---
Document: openxr_settings.rst
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/openxr_settings.rst
Summary: Explains the Local Floor reference space in OpenXR, its behavior, use cases, and potential pitfalls.
Local Floor reference space positions the origin where the player is, but keeps the player's height. Some XR runtimes persist this location over sessions. The player is not guaranteed to be standing at the origin, only that they were standing there when the user last recentered. The player is free to walk away. This reference space is best for games where the user is expected to stand in the same location or for AR games where interface elements are bound to the origin node and placed at the player's location on recenter. When the user recenters, the XR runtime moves the XRCamera3D above the XROrigin3D node while keeping the player's height. The OpenXRInterface emits the pose_recentered signal for game reaction.

Warning: Be careful using this mode with virtual player movement. User recentering can be unpredictable unless the move is countered when handling the recenter signal. This can be game breaking, causing the player to teleport to the origin's abstract location during virtual movement, potentially into off-limits areas. It is better to use Stage mode and limit resetting to orientation only when a pose_recentered signal is received.

Note: Any other XR tracked elements like controllers or anchors will also be adjusted accordingly.

Warning: You should not call center_on_hmd when using this reference space.
---CHUNK---
Document: OpenXR Settings
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/openxr_settings.rst
Summary: This section explains the environment blend mode settings for OpenXR in Godot.
The environment blend mode defines how the rendered output is blended into the real world, depending on headset capabilities.
- Opaque: The output obscures the real world, indicating VR mode.
- Additive: The output is added to the real world, suitable for AR modes where optics cannot fully obscure the real world (e.g., HoloLens).
- Alpha: The output is blended with the real world using alpha, requiring the viewport to have a transparent background enabled. This is for AR modes where optics can fully obscure the real world (e.g., Magic Leap, all pass-through devices).
If a selected mode is not supported by the headset, the first available mode will be used instead.
Note: Some OpenXR devices have separate systems for enabling/disabling passthrough. From Godot 4.3 onwards, selecting the alpha blend mode will also perform these extra steps, provided the latest vendor plugin is installed.
---CHUNK---
Document: OpenXR Settings
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/openxr_settings.rst
Summary: This section describes the Foveation Level setting in OpenXR, its purpose, and compatibility notes.
Foveation Level sets the foveation level used when rendering, provided this feature is supported by the hardware. Foveation is a technique where content is rendered at a lower resolution further away from the center of the viewport. Most XR runtimes only support fixed foveation, but some will take eye tracking into account and use the focal point for this effect. The higher the foveation level, the better the performance gains, but also the more reduction in quality there is in the user's peripheral vision.
Note: This setting is for the Compatibility renderer only. For Mobile and Forward+ renderers, set the vrs_mode property on Viewport to VRS_XR.
Warning: This feature is disabled if post effects are used such as glow, bloom, or DOF.
---CHUNK---
Document: OpenXR Settings
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/openxr_settings.rst
Summary: Describes the Foveation Dynamic setting in OpenXR.
Foveation Dynamic: When enabled, the foveation level is automatically adjusted based on current GPU load, varying between low and the foveation level selected in the previous setting. It is recommended to combine this setting with the foveation level set to high. Note: Compatibility renderer only.
---CHUNK---
Document: OpenXR Settings
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/openxr_settings.rst
Summary: Describes the "Submit Depth Buffer" setting in OpenXR and its implications.
Submit Depth Buffer: If enabled, an OpenXR-supplied depth buffer will be used during rendering and submitted alongside the rendered image. The XR runtime can use this for improved reprojection. Note: Enabling this feature will disable stencil support during rendering. Not many XR runtimes make use of this; it is advised to leave this setting off unless it provides noticeable benefits for your use case.
---CHUNK---
Document: OpenXR Settings
Path: godot/tutorials/xr/openxr_settings.rst
Summary: This section describes the "Startup Alert" setting in OpenXR and common reasons for OpenXR initialization failure.
Startup Alert
If enabled, this will result in an alert message presented to the user if OpenXR fails to start. We don't always receive feedback from the XR system as to why starting fails. If we do, we log this to the console. Common failure reasons are:
* No OpenXR runtime is installed on the host system.
* Microsoft's WMR OpenXR runtime is currently active, this only supports DirectX and will fail if OpenGL or Vulkan is used.
* SteamVR is used but no headset is connected/turned on.
Disable this if you support a fallback mode in your game so it can be played in desktop mode when no VR headset is connected, or if you're handling the failure condition yourself by checking OpenXRInterface.is_initialized().
---CHUNK---
